			<h5>Townhall Registration</h5>
			<p>This can be considered your first step to integration into Spanish life, registration means that you are an official resident of your community. Second, the empadronamiento is the way that your stay or residence in Spain is verified or accredited – a necessity for a variety of administrative procedures.</p>
			<br>
			<div class="row">
				<div class="col-md-6">
					<div class="wrapper">
						<strong>Services/actions that require you to be registered:</strong>
						<ul>
							<li>Enroll your children in local schools.</li>
							<li>Get married.</li>
							<li>Apply for a local health card.</li>
							<li>Vote.</li>
							<li>Apply for certain visas.</li>
							<li>Apply for certain passports, depending your nationality.</li>
							<li>Apply for residency by way of a general amnesty or arraigo.</li>
						</ul>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<br>
			It also allows you to take advantage of local leisure facilities with discounted fees at the municipal sports centre and excercise classes. It is often necessary when looking for work via the municipal ‘job center’ equivalent. There are numerous advantages to having a certificate of empadronamiento, like discounts on road tax, council tax (IBI) and more.
			<br><br>
			To register you need to go to your local town hall and produce your <strong>passport, Residencia and a copy of your escritura (title deeds, home owners only) or rental contract</strong> and you will be registered. If you say that you need proof that you are registered, they will issue you with a certificate, signed by the mayor.
